  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "What are some bad habits that self-taught programmers develop?",
  "response": "Self-taught programmers often develop some habits that can negatively impact their productivity and code quality. Here are some common bad habits:\n\n1. **Skipping Documentation:** They often neglect to write or read documentation, leading to misunderstandings and difficulties when maintaining or sharing code.\n\n2. **Poor Code Comments:** They might write insufficient or unclear comments, or over-comment obvious code, which can make the code harder to understand and maintain.\n\n3. **Inconsistent Coding Style:** Without guidance, self-taught programmers may develop inconsistent coding practices, making their code harder for others to read and collaborate on.\n\n4. **Over-Reliance on Google and Stack Overflow:** While these resources are helpful, relying too much on copy-pasting solutions without understanding them can lead to shallow knowledge and potential security vulnerabilities.\n\n5. **Neglecting Testing:** They might skip writing tests or write inadequate tests, leading to more bugs and unreliable software.\n\n6. **Ignoring Best Practices:** They might be unaware of or ignore best practices for coding, security, and performance, leading to poor code quality.\n\n7. **Lack of Version Control:** They might not use version control systems effectively, making it difficult to track changes and collaborate with others.\n\n8. **Reinventing the Wheel:** They might waste time writing code for problems that have well-established solutions and libraries, impeding productivity and potential alienation from the current standards.\n\n9. **Limited Design Patterns Knowledge:** They might lack understanding of common design patterns, leading to inefficient problem-solving and complex, hard-to-maintain code structures.\n\n10. **Inadequate Error Handling:** They might not implement robust error handling, resulting in software that fails unpredictably and is difficult to debug.\n\n11. **Bad Time Management:** They might spend too much time on specific problems without managing their time well, leading to inefficiency.\n\n12. **Undervaluing Soft Skills:** Communication, teamwork, and understanding user requirements can be undervalued, leading to difficulties in collaborating and delivering user-friendly solutions.\n\nAddressing these habits involves continuous learning, seeking feedback from other programmers, and actively adopting good practices, such as code reviews, using and contributing to open-source projects, and participating in developer communities.",
